oving from the universal, spatial concept of the Tokugawa period, through temporal, social Darwinian ideas of inevitable progress and competitive struggle, to a celebration of Japan as a nation uniquely in harmony with nature. The so-called traditional "Japanese love of nature" masks modern state power.Thomas's theoretically sophisticated study rejects the supposition that modernity is the ideological antithesis of nature, overcoming the determinism of the physical environment through technology and liberating denatured subjects from the chains of biology and tradition. In making "nature" available as a critical term for political analysis, this book yields new insights into prewar Japan's failure to achieve liberal democracy, as well as an alternative means of understanding modernity and the position of non-Western nations within it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNaturexEffect of human beings onzJapan. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aasia.  abiology.  acolonial empire.  acolonialism.  acompetition.  aeast asia.  aempire.  aenvironment.  aenvironmentalism.  afeudalism.  aharmony.  aindustrial revolution.  ajapan.  ajapanese colonialism.  ajapanese history.  ajapanese imperialism.  ajapanese literature.  ajapanese studies.  aliberal democracy.  ameiji history.  amodern japan.  amodernity.  anatural world.  anature.  anonfiction.  aphysical environment.  apolitical authority.  apolitical power.  apolitics.  aprewar japan.  aprogress.  asocial darwinism.  astate power.  atechnology.  atokugawa.  atradition.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022854240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092684440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978052092684